00:52:13,832 --> 00:52:16,301
You wanna play rough?

695
00:52:26,261 --> 00:52:28,763
Hey, where you goin'?

696
00:52:31,983 --> 00:52:34,985
Watts: When did you first know
you wanted to design engines?

697
00:52:34,986 --> 00:52:37,688
February 14, 1976.

698
00:52:37,689 --> 00:52:39,690
It was the Daytona 500.

699
00:52:39,691 --> 00:52:41,191
What a race that was.

700
00:52:41,192 --> 00:52:45,245
Richard petty... he was
the man to beat that year.

701
00:52:45,246 --> 00:52:48,332
He was comin' off
of 13 wins in '75.

702
00:52:48,333 --> 00:52:51,335
He looked like a shoo-in

703
00:52:51,336 --> 00:52:54,621
to take home his
record breaking sixth 500.

704
00:52:54,622 --> 00:52:57,007
Held the lead for
almost the entire race.

705
00:52:57,008 --> 00:53:00,010
Then on the last lap,

706
00:53:00,011 --> 00:53:05,132
David Pearson
pulls out of petty's draft,

707
00:53:05,133 --> 00:53:07,935
and both cars start
spinnin' and crashin'.

708
00:53:07,936 --> 00:53:10,020
It was... it was chaos.

709
00:53:10,021 --> 00:53:13,023
Debris flyin' everywhere.

710
00:53:13,024 --> 00:53:16,193
It was one of the most
exciting finishes

711
00:53:16,194 --> 00:53:18,695
the 500 ever had.

712
00:53:18,696 --> 00:53:21,198
And I didn't see any of it.

713
00:53:22,567 --> 00:53:24,484
What?

714
00:53:24,485 --> 00:53:30,490
Because at the moment
that Pearson was making his move on petty,

715
00:53:30,491 --> 00:53:33,994
I found myself staring
down in pit row

716
00:53:33,995 --> 00:53:36,496
at the most beautiful
girl I'd ever seen

717
00:53:36,497 --> 00:53:37,998
in a mechanic's jumpsuit.

718
00:53:40,051 --> 00:53:42,052
She was standing up
on this retaining wall,

719
00:53:42,053 --> 00:53:44,555
yellin' her head off.

720
00:53:44,556 --> 00:53:47,558
But even from
where I was sitting,

721
00:53:47,559 --> 00:53:52,062
you could still see
that fire in her eyes, you know?

722
00:53:52,063 --> 00:53:53,564
That was mom.

723
00:53:53,565 --> 00:53:55,599
Yeah.

724
00:53:55,600 --> 00:53:59,603
And I realized that moment
two things:

725
00:53:59,604 --> 00:54:04,107
What I wanted to do
with the rest of my life,

726
00:54:04,108 --> 00:54:06,360
and who I wanted
to spend it with.

727
00:54:09,664 --> 00:54:12,667
It was what you might call
a defining moment.

728
00:54:31,302 --> 00:54:32,303
Hey, Scott.

729
00:54:34,138 --> 00:54:36,723
What do you think
of my son Rodney?

730
00:54:36,724 --> 00:54:38,225
Kid's got some talent.

731
00:54:38,226 --> 00:54:39,226
Some.

732
00:54:39,227 --> 00:54:40,227
Man: This way, Scott.

733
00:54:40,228 --> 00:54:41,778
Great. Thanks.

734
00:54:41,779 --> 00:54:43,530
Excuse me, Scott.

735
00:54:43,531 --> 00:54:46,199
Um, I'm a local racer,

736
00:54:46,200 --> 00:54:49,119
